n=left class=m><span class=title>   Sensi's farewell...</span><hr size=1> As many of you know, I retired from EQ a couple months ago. When revisiting a message board the other day the urge overcame me to write her final RP exit as well. This story borrows heavily from Homer's Iliad, both in style and image. It can also be found on the net at <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://members.home.net/sensi-jadeleaf">members.home.net/sensi-jadeleaf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> sans</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> images, since I'm having troubles with my ISP. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
--<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Only the most fragmentary remains of the scrolls of Sentii Jadeleaf, written some four millennia ago, survive to this day. They seem to document the life of her family, the Jadeleafs, and most prominently of a bard named Sensi, her sister. Here follows a translation of the passage entitled, “The Great Raid”. The Tier’dal had mounted a massive attack on Faydwer. This documents her sister’s brave fight against the dark armies, and her subsequent death at the hands of an ambush patrol lead by Lucan, the infamous leader of the extinct Freeport Militia.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
….so till the sun bestrode the sky at high noon<br>
the weapons hurtled side-to-side and men kept falling.<br>
But once the sun wheeled past the hour for unyoking cattle,<br>
then the Fier’dal mounted a fiercer new attack,<br>
fighting beyond their fates…<br>
<br>
and Sensi charged the enemy, fired for the kill.<br>
Three times she charged with the headlong speed of Selo,<br>
bellowing her savage cry, three times she killed nine men.<br>
Then at the fourth assault Sensi like something superhuman –<br>
Then, Sensi, the end of life came blazing up before you,<br>
Yes, the lord Cazic met you there in the heart of battle,<br>
the god, the terror! Sensi never saw him coming,<br>
moving across the deadly rout, shrouded in thick mist<br>
and on he came against her and looming up behind her now –<br>
slammed her strong shoulders and back with the god’s flat hand<br>
and her eyes spun as Cazic knocked the helmet off her head<br>
and under the army’s boots it tumbled, clattering on<br>
with its four forged horns and its hollow blank eyes<br>
and its plumes were all smeared in the bloody dust.<br>
Sensi though – the spear in her grip was shattered,<br>
the whole of its rugged steel-shod shadow-casting length<br>
and her lute with straps and tassels dropped from her shoulders,<br>
flung down on the ground – and lord Cazic the god of Fear<br>
wrenched her breastplate off. Disasater seized her –<br>
her fine legs buckling –<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp she stood there, senseless –<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And now,<br>
right at her back, close-up, a Tier’dal fighter speared her<br>
squarely between the shoulder blades with a sharp lance.<br>
Augine’s daughter Sithia , the best of her own age<br>
at spears and a warrior’s skill and speed of blade,<br>
and even in this, her first attack with an army –<br>
just learning the arts of war –<br>
she’d brought down twenty casters in their concentration.<br>
She was the first to launch a spear against you,<br>
Sensi O my sister, but did not bring you down.<br>
Yanking out her ashen shaft from your body,<br>
Back she dashed and lost herself in the crowds –<br>
the woman would not stand up to Sensi here<br>
in mortal combat, stripped, defenseless as she was.<br>
Sensi stunned by the spear and the god’s crushing blow<br>
was weaving back to her own thronging comrades,<br>
trying to escape death…<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lucan waiting, watching<br>
the greathearted Sensi trying to stagger free,<br>
seeing her wounded there with the sharp steel<br>
came rushing into her right across the lines<br>
and rammed his great sword home,<br>
stabbing deep in the bowels, and the flaming point<br>
went jutting straight out through Sensi’s back.<br>
Down she crashed – horror gripped the Fier’dalian armies.<br>
so now with a close thrust Lucan son of Jinn<br>
tore the life from the fighting daughter of Tunare,<br>
from Sensi who had killed so many men in war,<br>
and gloried over her, wild winging words: “Sensi –<br>
you fool! Rearing in ambush was my army,<br>
Militia forces were charging out to battle,<br>
Charging, full speed. And I with my spear,<br>
Lucan, shining among my combat-loving comrades,<br>
I fight away from them the fatal day – but you,<br>
the vultures will eat your body raw!”<br>
<br>
Struggling for breath, you answered, Sensi O my sister,<br>
“Lucan! Now is your time to glory to the skies…<br>
now the victory is yours.<br>
A gift of the god of fear, Cazic – Innoruuk too –<br>
they brought me down with all their deathless ease,<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> they</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are the ones who tore the armour off my back.<br>
Even if twenty Lucans had charged against me –<br>
they'd all have died here, laid low by my spear.<br>
No, deadly fate in league with Cazic killed me.<br>
From the ranks of men, Sithia. You came third,<br>
and all you could do was finish off my life…<br>
One more thing – take it to heart, I urge you –<br>
you too, you won’t live long yourself, I swear.<br>
Already I see them looming up beside you – death<br>
and the strong force of fate, to bring you down<br>
at the hands of Jadeleaf’s great royal daughter…<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Kataria!”<br>
<br>
Death cut her short. The end closed in around her.<br>
Flying free of her limbs<br>
her soul went winging down to the House of Death,<br>
wailing her fate, leaving her friends far behind,<br>
her young and supple strength. But glorious Lucan<br>
taunted Sensi’s body, dead as she was, “Why, Sensi –<br>
why prophesy my doom, my sudden death? Who knows? –<br>
Your daughter, the sisters of sleek-haired Sensi may outrace me –<br>
struck by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> my</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spear first – and gasp away their life!”<br>
<br>
With that he planted a heel against Sensi’s chest,<br>
wrenched his firey blade from the wound, kicked her over<br>
flat on her back, free and clear of the weapon.<br>
<br>
and so they buried Sensi, singer of Bristlebane. <p><b>Sensi Jadeleaf</b><BR>
